p-right''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxborder-left header-fauxborder-left''>\n<div class=''fauxborder-right header-fauxborder-right''></div>\n<div class=''region-inner header-inner''>\n<div class=''header section'' id=''header''><div class=''widget Header'' id=''Header1''>\n<div id=''header-inner''>\n<div class=''titlewrapper''>\n<h1 class=''title''>\n<a href=''http://www.benlesh.com/''>Try, Catch, Fail</a>\n</h1>\n</div>\n<div class=''descriptionwrapper''>\n<p class=''description''><span>I''m not doing this to "teach", I''m doing this to LEARN. Your feedback and corrections are absolutely welcome!</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''header-cap-bottom cap-bottom''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</header>\n<div class=''tabs-outer''>\n<div class=''tabs-cap-top cap-top''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxborder-left tabs-fauxborder-left''>\n<div class=''fauxborder-right tabs-fauxborder-right''></div>\n<div class=''region-inner tabs-inner''>\n<div class=''tabs section'' id=''crosscol''></div>\n<div class=''tabs section'' id=''crosscol-overflow''></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''tabs-cap-bottom cap-bottom''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''main-outer''>\n<div class=''main-cap-top cap-top''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxborder-left main-fauxborder-left''>\n<div class=''fauxborder-right main-fauxborder-right''></div>\n<div class=''region-inner main-inner''>\n<div class=''columns fauxcolumns''>\n<div class=''fauxcolumn-outer fauxcolumn-center-outer''>\n<div class=''cap-top''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxborder-left''>\n<div class=''fauxborder-right''></div>\n<div class=''fauxcolumn-inner''>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''cap-bottom''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxcolumn-outer fauxcolumn-left-outer''>\n<div class=''cap-top''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxborder-left''>\n<div class=''fauxborder-right''></div>\n<div class=''fauxcolumn-inner''>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''cap-bottom''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxcolumn-outer fauxcolumn-right-outer''>\n<div class=''cap-top''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''fauxborder-left''>\n<div class=''fauxborder-right''></div>\n<div class=''fauxcolumn-inner''>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''cap-bottom''>\n<div class=''cap-left''></div>\n<div class=''cap-right''></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<!-- corrects IE6 width calculation -->\n<div class=''columns-inner''>\n<div class=''column-center-outer''>\n<div class=''column-center-inner''>\n<div class=''main section'' id=''main''><div class=''widget Blog'' id=''Blog1''>\n<div class=''blog-posts hfeed''>\n<!-- google_ad_section_start(name=default) -->\n\n          <div class="date-outer">\n        \n<h2 class=''date-header''><span>Wednesday, February 13, 2013</span></h2>\n\n          <div class="date-posts">\n        \n<div class=''post-outer''>\n<div class=''post hentry'' itemscope=''itemscope'' itemtype=''http://schema.org/BlogPosting''>\n<a name=''1753634449913372984''></a>\n<h3 class=''post-title entry-title'' itemprop=''name''>\nAngularJS: Creating A Service With $http\n</h3>\n<div class=''post-header''>\n<div class=''post-header-line-1''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''post-body entry-content'' id=''post-body-1753634449913372984'' itemprop=''articleBody''>\nSo I did a talk on <a href="http://angularjs.org/">AngularJS </a>last night at the <a href="http://www.meetup.com/pghdotnet/">Pittsburgh .NET Users'' Group</a>. It was a great talk and you guys asked a lot of great questions. One of my friends that attended suggest people use my blog as a resource for Angular, and while I do have quite a few posts about Angular, I don''t feel like it''s quite as flushed out in that department as I''d like it to be before I wanted my friends plugging it like that. So I''ve decided to try to fill that gap, at least as far as Angular goes, over the next few weeks, if I can. (Don''t worry, PGHNUG attendees, I''ll still try to get a well commented Angular/Web API solution up on GitHub soon).<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<h3>\nHTTP Service Calls In Angular</h3>\n<div>\n<br />\nOne of the most common questions I see on <a href="http://www.stackoverflow.com/">StackOverflow </a>regarding Angular, are questions involving the creation of AJAX-based angular services using <a href="http://docs.angularjs.org/api/ng.$http">$http</a>. Commonly the pattern used is very&nbsp;reminiscent&nbsp;of JQuery, where there''s a method with a callback when the data is&nbsp;received.<br />\n<br />\n<h4>\nCommon Callback Example</h4>\n<br />\n<pre class="prettyprint">app.factory(''myService'', function($http) {\n   return {\n     getFooOldSchool: function(callback) {\n       $http.get(''foo.json'').success(callback);\n     }\n   }\n});\n\napp.controller(''MainCtrl'', function($scope, myService) {\n  myService.getFooOldSchool(function(data) {\n     $scope.foo = data;\n  });\n});\n</pre>\n<br />\n<br />\nThat''s fine. It''s an easy to understand pattern that is predictable for most other developers using your service and most importantly, it works.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<h3>\nAngular Loves Promises</h3>\nIn Angular, there is a <a href="http://docs.angularjs.org/api/ng.$q">service called $q</a>. It is a deferred/promise implementation built off of <a href="http://documentup.com/kriskowal/q/">Q by Kristopher Kowal</a>. I know I''ve talked about <a href="http://www.benlesh.com/2012/09/javascript-promises-promises.html">deferment and promises in JavaScript</a> in the past, but as a very quick refresher, the idea behind this pattern is basically to have a mechanism to signal when one (or sometimes many) asynchronous actions are complete. It''s the hub of JQuery''s AJAX implementation, Angular $http implementation and Angular''s $resource implementation. I like this mechanism so much I''ve even implemented it in my <a href="http://github.com/blesh/ALE">.NET Event Loop Framework</a>.<br />\n<br />\n<h3>\n<span style="color: red;">EDIT: As of 1.2.0, promises are no longer resolved by templates.</span></h3>\n<strike>So in code, that means if you return a promise from your service, and put it directly in a scope property, it will asynchronously update that scope property and process the changes.</strike><br />\n<br />\nSince $http methods like get() and post() return promises, we can use that promise''s then() method (which also returns a promise) to pull the data out of the result. The return value from the then() method''s callback is used to resolve that promise.<br />\n<br />\n<h4>\nSimplified Promise Pattern Example</h4>\n<br />\n<pre class="prettyprint">app.factory(''myService'', function($http) {\n   return {\n     getFoo: function() {\n       //since $http.get returns a promise,\n       //and promise.then() also returns a promise\n       //that resolves to whatever value is returned in it''s \n       //callback argument, we can return that.\n       return $http.get(''foo.json'').then(function(result) {\n           return result.data;\n       });\n     }\n   }\n});\n\napp.controller(''MainCtrl'', function($scope, myService) {\n   //DEPRECATED: The commented line below WILL NO LONGER WORK in 1.2.0\n   //since promises are no longer resolved by templates.\n   //$scope.foo = myService.getFoo();\n\n   //make the call to getFoo and handle the promise returned;\n   myService.getFoo().then(function(data) {\n       //this will execute when the \n       //AJAX call completes.\n       $scope.foo2 = data;\n       console.log(data);\n   });\n};\n</pre>\n<br />\n<br />\n<br />\nAnd because some of you like to play around, <a href="http://plnkr.co/edit/3Eoq0zmv5NnOpHvyccaS?p=preview">here''s a bit of code on plunker</a> showing the promise pattern for $http calls in Angular:<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<iframe allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" frameborder="0" src="http://embed.plnkr.co/Kw7BEFqYhpAjKuUAUxQh" style="height: 300px; width: 100%;"></iframe>\n\n<br />\n<h2>\nEdit: Complex $http calls from within a Service</h2>\n<br />\nBecause I''ve been asked by friends what to do in situations where you might have nested or simultaneous async calls in a controller, I think this blog entry is a really good place to show some examples of that, since it falls under the same domain, so to speak.<br />\n<br />\nThere are of course scenarios where you might have a service method that requires more than one $http call (or other async call) to be made before you want the service to return. This is where you''d want to use the $q service mentioned above.<br />\n<br />\n<h4>\nExample of dealing with multiple async calls to return simultaneously</h4>\n<br />\n<pre class="prettyprint">app.factory(''myService'', function ($http, $q){\n  return {\n    getItems: function (){\n      //$q.all will wait for an array of promises to resolve,\n      // then will resolve it''s own promise (which it returns)\n      // with an array of results in the same order.\n      return $q.all([\n        $http.get(''items_part_1.json''),\n          $http.get(''items_part_2.json'')\n      ])\n        \n      //process all of the results from the two promises \n      // above, and join them together into a single result.\n      // since then() returns a promise that resolves ot the\n      // return value of it''s callback, this is all we need \n      // to return from our service method.\n      .then(function(results) {\n        var data = [];\n        angular.forEach(results, function(result) {\n          data = data.concat(result.data);\n        });\n        return data;\n      });\n    }\n  };\n});\n</pre>\n<br />\n<br />\nExample of dealing with nested async calls in a single service call<br />\n<br />\nTechnically, we can deal with nested async calls without using $q. ("nested" to say that each call to $http triggers a subsequent call to $http in order to build out some data) This simplifies the code a little, but in my opinion makes it harder to follow. &nbsp;For example:\n<br />\n<br />\n<pre class="prettyprint"> getNestedData: function (){ \n      // get the parents.\n      return $http.get(''parents.json'')\n        .then(function(result) {          \n          //return a promise to that data.\n          return result.data;\n        })\n        //handle the promise to the parent data\n        .then(function(parents) {         \n          //get the children.\n          return $http.get(''children.json'')\n            //handle the promise to the children.\n            .then(function(result) {            \n              //add children to the appropriate parent(s).\n              var children = result.data;\n              angular.forEach(parents, function(parent) {\n                parent.children = [];            \n                angular.forEach(children, function(child) {\n                  if(parent.childIds.indexOf(child.id) &gt;= 0) {\n                    parent.children.push(child);\n                  }\n                });\n              });              \n              //return the parents\n              return parents;\n            });\n        });\n    }\n</pre>\n<br />\n<br />\nExample of nested calls using $q directly\n<br />\n<br />\nThis is a point where it really doesn''t matter which route you go when it comes to what''s going to work. However, it is my opinion that using $q directly in complicated async calls or nested async calls, enhances readability. This is simply because it becomes easier to see which promise was returned, when it was created, and where it was resolved:<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<pre class="prettyprint">getNestedDataBetter: function (){\n  //create your deferred promise.\n  var deferred = $q.defer();\n  \n  //do your thing.\n  $http.get(''parents.json'')\n    .then(function(result){\n      var parents = result.data;\n      $http.get(''children.json'')\n        .then(function(result) {\n          var children = result.data;\n            angular.forEach(parents, function(parent) {\n              parent.children = [];            \n              angular.forEach(children, function(child) {\n                if(parent.childIds.indexOf(child.id) &gt;= 0) {\n                  parent.children.push(child);\n                }\n              });\n            }); \n            \n            //at whatever point in your code, you feel your\n            // code has loaded all necessary data and/or\n            // resolve your promise.\n            deferred.resolve(parents);\n        });\n    });\n    \n  //return your promise to the user.\n  return deferred.promise;\n}\n</pre>\n<br />\n<br />\nAnd here''s a plunk of the more complicated examples:\n<br />\n<br />\n<iframe allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" frameborder="0" src="http://embed.plnkr.co/9ZFJUlagx4rILondZhMx" style="height: 300px; width: 100%;"></iframe>\n\n</div>\n<div style=''clear: both;''></div>\n</div>\n<div class=''post-footer''>\n<div class=''post-footer-line post-footer-line-1''><span class=''post-author vcard''>\nPosted by\n<span class=''fn''>\n<a href=''https://plus.google.com/102417241717350168090'' itemprop=''author'' rel=''author'' title=''author profile''>\nBen Lesh\n</a>\n</span>\n</span>\n<span class=''post-timestamp''>\nat\n<a class=''timestamp-link'' href=''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html'' itemprop=''url'' rel=''bookmark'' title=''permanent link''><abbr class=''published'' itemprop=''datePublished'' title=''2013-02-13T18:09:00-08:00''>6:09 PM</abbr></a>\n</span>\n<span class=''post-comment-link''>\n</span>\n<span class=''post-icons''>\n<span class=''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''>\n<a href=''http://www.blogger.com/post-edit.g?blogID=6203468128981313022&postID=1753634449913372984&from=pencil'' title=''Edit Post''>\n<img alt='''' class=''icon-action'' height=''18'' src=''http://img2.blogblog.com/img/icon18_edit_allbkg.gif'' width=''18''/>\n</a>\n</span>\n</span>\n<div class=''post-share-buttons goog-inline-block''>\n<a class=''goog-inline-block share-button sb-email'' href=''http://www.blogger.com/share-post.g?blogID=6203468128981313022&postID=1753634449913372984&target=email'' target=''_blank'' title=''Email This''><span class=''share-button-link-text''>Email This</span></a><a class=''goog-inline-block share-button sb-blog'' href=''http://www.blogger.com/share-post.g?blogID=6203468128981313022&postID=1753634449913372984&target=blog'' onclick=''window.open(this.href, "_blank", "height=270,width=475"); return false;'' target=''_blank'' title=''BlogThis!''><span class=''share-button-link-text''>BlogThis!</span></a><a class=''goog-inline-block share-button sb-twitter'' href=''http://www.blogger.com/share-post.g?blogID=6203468128981313022&postID=1753634449913372984&target=twitter'' target=''_blank'' title=''Share to Twitter''><span class=''share-button-link-text''>Share to Twitter</span></a><a class=''goog-inline-block share-button sb-facebook'' href=''http://www.blogger.com/share-post.g?blogID=6203468128981313022&postID=1753634449913372984&target=facebook'' onclick=''window.open(this.href, "_blank", "height=430,width=640"); return false;'' target=''_blank'' title=''Share to Facebook''><span class=''share-button-link-text''>Share to Facebook</span></a><a class=''goog-inline-block share-button sb-pinterest'' href=''http://www.blogger.com/share-post.g?blogID=6203468128981313022&postID=1753634449913372984&target=pinterest'' target=''_blank'' title=''Share to Pinterest''><span class=''share-button-link-text''>Share to Pinterest</span></a><div class=''goog-inline-block dummy-container''><g:plusone source=''blogger:blog:plusone'' href=''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html'' size=''medium'' width=''300'' annotation=''inline''/></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''post-footer-line post-footer-line-2''><span class=''post-labels''>\nLabels:\n<a href=''http://www.benlesh.com/search/label/AJAX'' rel=''tag''>AJAX</a>,\n<a href=''http://www.benlesh.com/search/label/AngularJS'' rel=''tag''>AngularJS</a>,\n<a href=''http://www.benlesh.com/search/label/Async'' rel=''tag''>Async</a>,\n<a href=''http://www.benlesh.com/search/label/JavaScript'' rel=''tag''>JavaScript</a>,\n<a href=''http://www.benlesh.com/search/label/Web%20Development'' rel=''tag''>Web Development</a>\n</span>\n</div>\n<div class=''post-footer-line post-footer-line-3''><span class=''post-location''>\n</span>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=''comments'' id=''comments''>\n<a name=''comments''></a>\n<h4>32 comments:</h4>\n<div class=''comments-content''>\n<script async=''async'' src=''//www.blogblog.com/dynamicviews/4224c15c4e7c9321/js/comments.js'' type=''text/javascript''></script>\n<script type=''text/javascript''>\n    (function() {\n      var items = [{''id'': ''4591238218356147709'', ''body'': ''heh heh ;)\\74br /\\76useful as always...'', ''timestamp'': ''1361286042434'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751361286042434#c4591238218356147709'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Jeremy Wells'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ox4bVw_ctJ0/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAEs/EehiQYSvRLo/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/17960637484147310942''}, ''displayTime'': ''February 19, 2013 at 7:00 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-611173119''}, {''id'': ''4303846535106231411'', ''body'': ''Nice! One question: How can I access the foo var in the controller?\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76app.controller(\\46#39;MainCtrl\\46#39;, function($scope, myService) {\\74br /\\76   //the clean and simple way\\74br /\\76   $scope.foo \\75 myService.getFoo();\\74br /\\76    console.log($scope.foo[0].name); // I want to use the first name from json array!\\74br /\\76};\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76Thanks.'', ''timestamp'': ''1362525460042'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751362525460042#c4303846535106231411'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Alan Löffler'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/--9Dqwb_9DKs/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAD0/9zdCGKhIp28/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/09491233622750487231''}, ''displayTime'': ''March 5, 2013 at 3:17 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-592126214''}, {''id'': ''3682614050155498157'', ''parentId'': ''4303846535106231411'', ''body'': ''I\\46#39;ve updated the post to reflect this, since it\\46#39;s a common scenario... If there\\46#39;s a situation where you need to wait for the value to return, you can either: \\74br /\\76\\74br /\\0761. use the promise\\46#39;s then() function: \\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76$scope.getFoo().then(function(data) {\\74br /\\76   $scope.foo \\75 data;\\74br /\\76   console.log(data[0].name);\\74br /\\76});\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76or 2. use a $watch\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76$scope.$watch(\\46#39;foo\\46#39;, function(v) {\\74br /\\76   console.log(v[0].name);\\74br /\\76});'', ''timestamp'': ''1362580188526'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751362580188526#c3682614050155498157'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''March 6, 2013 at 6:29 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''8381469538113812922'', ''body'': ''Very clear and concise. Helped me understand the concept of promises in Angular. Thanks!'', ''timestamp'': ''1366722007646'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751366722007646#c8381469538113812922'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Chris'', ''avatarUrl'': ''http://img1.blogblog.com/img/blank.gif'', ''profileUrl'': ''''}, ''displayTime'': ''April 23, 2013 at 6:00 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-842670084''}, {''id'': ''2902382397672874025'', ''body'': ''Thank you xD'', ''timestamp'': ''1367535269374'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751367535269374#c2902382397672874025'', ''author'': {''name'': ''MOstafa Radi'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh4.googleusercontent.com/-U2e8j2nZwHE/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAA8/sjieRjFsBG4/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/14962327110123804123''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 2, 2013 at 3:54 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-626444538''}, {''id'': ''7764818909968384934'', ''body'': ''No need for $q if you have a promise, just chain them:\\74br /\\76app.factory(\\46#39;myService\\46#39;, function($http) {\\74br /\\76   return {\\74br /\\76     getFoo: function() {\\74br /\\76       return $http.get(\\46#39;foo.json\\46#39;).then(function(response) {\\74br /\\76          return response.data;\\74br /\\76       });\\74br /\\76     }\\74br /\\76   }\\74br /\\76});'', ''timestamp'': ''1368794922047'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751368794922047#c7764818909968384934'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Brad'', ''avatarUrl'': ''http://img2.blogblog.com/img/b16-rounded.gif'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/18124460375969044847''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 17, 2013 at 5:48 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-1021009290''}, {''id'': ''1195069714156375713'', ''parentId'': ''7764818909968384934'', ''body'': ''Very good point. I guess I like the explicitness of $q. But I hadn\\46#39;t thought of that.'', ''timestamp'': ''1368810928070'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751368810928070#c1195069714156375713'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 17, 2013 at 10:15 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''2831252964682292753'', ''parentId'': ''7764818909968384934'', ''body'': ''Okay, I just ran into the reason why I use $q rather than the method you\\46#39;ve outlined. In particular, if you have a web method that returns true or false. For example a check for a username availability, and you return using the method you\\46#39;ve described above, you\\46#39;ll run into scenarios where the result will be type coerced to be *true* since it\\46#39;s returning the $http\\46#39;s prior to updating it to the inner deferred result. So it\\46#39;s generally best practice to use $q in these scenarios, so you\\46#39;re not returning a promise to a promise, you\\46#39;re just returning a promise... if that makes sense. (Your method will work fine in some scenarios though)'', ''timestamp'': ''1369018333173'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751369018333173#c2831252964682292753'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 19, 2013 at 7:52 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''9016002742285148033'', ''parentId'': ''7764818909968384934'', ''body'': ''but it doesnt return a promise to a promise. it returns a promise to the return result of the inner function. \\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76if i have:\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76var promise \\75 $http.get(\\46#39;/username/\\46#39;+username+\\46#39;/_available\\46#39;).then(function(response){ return response.data; });\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76and i do:\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76promise.then(function(value){\\74br /\\76   console.log(value);\\74br /\\76});\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76the console will log the response.data property, not a promise. here\\46#39;s a plunk:\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76http://plnkr.co/edit/E6g9RYwRSFPFptZ7iqAK?p\\75preview\\74br /\\076'', ''timestamp'': ''1369054723687'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751369054723687#c9016002742285148033'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Brad'', ''avatarUrl'': ''http://img2.blogblog.com/img/b16-rounded.gif'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/18124460375969044847''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 20, 2013 at 5:58 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-1021009290''}, {''id'': ''7381493592188389097'', ''parentId'': ''7764818909968384934'', ''body'': ''Well, a \\46quot;promise to a promise\\46quot; isn\\46#39;t accurate, I guess. And in the scenario where you\\46#39;re doing all of your $http calls from within your controller, I suppose what you\\46#39;re doing here is okay. The problem comes in when you try to create something a little more robust by abstracting your $http calls into a custom angular service... which was precisely what this post was about.\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76The issue is that without $q, you\\46#39;ll have to use a process the response, then use a callback to handle it in your controller. Callbacks are ugly, inflexible, and unfortunately all too prevalent thanks to older versions of JQuery.\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76Here is a demonstration of exactly what I mean: http://plnkr.co/edit/WWAuZqsbAsCXolJAb28l?p\\75preview\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76Using $q to process and return the response from your service will be cleaner, more flexible and overall better than the alternatives. Especially with the slick way that Angular handles returns on $scope properties.'', ''timestamp'': ''1369061414301'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751369061414301#c7381493592188389097'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 20, 2013 at 7:50 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''8480268017944708516'', ''body'': ''you almost had it. $http().success() returns the response\\46#39;s data property, not the response itself. change foo() to this:\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76    foo: function (){\\74br /\\76      return $http.get(\\46#39;foo.txt\\46#39;).then(function(result){\\74br /\\76        return result.data \\75\\75\\75 \\46#39;true\\46#39;;\\74br /\\76      });\\74br /\\76    }'', ''timestamp'': ''1369065557335'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751369065557335#c8480268017944708516'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Brad'', ''avatarUrl'': ''http://img2.blogblog.com/img/b16-rounded.gif'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/18124460375969044847''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 20, 2013 at 8:59 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-1021009290''}, {''id'': ''2015178987236372540'', ''parentId'': ''8480268017944708516'', ''body'': ''I see, you\\46#39;re using then() rather than success(). Good info. Thanks. '', ''timestamp'': ''1369067227698'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751369067227698#c2015178987236372540'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''May 20, 2013 at 9:27 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''8666641038118483908'', ''body'': ''Hi, so then, is there any point of using $q with $http? Thanks. '', ''timestamp'': ''1371245183268'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751371245183268#c8666641038118483908'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Agustín Treceño'', ''avatarUrl'': ''http://img2.blogblog.com/img/b16-rounded.gif'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/00311553591624583515''}, ''displayTime'': ''June 14, 2013 at 2:26 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-1834170586''}, {''id'': ''3344860675009815739'', ''parentId'': ''8666641038118483908'', ''body'': ''Absolutely. In the event that you want to additionally scrub the results of your response into another model. Or in the event you\\46#39;d like to have a service method wait for two $http calls (nested or unnested) to return.'', ''timestamp'': ''1371266885584'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751371266885584#c3344860675009815739'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''June 14, 2013 at 8:28 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''9137058484922890611'', ''body'': ''This is an old post, but I see some recent comments so I\\46#39;ll chime in.\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76You actually don\\46#39;t need to use either $q OR nest your $http calls for running multiple $http calls. This will work:\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76return $http.get(\\46#39;parents.json\\46#39;)\\74br /\\76  .then(function( parents ) {\\74br /\\76    return $http.get(\\46#39;children.json\\46#39;);\\74br /\\76  })\\74br /\\76  .then(function( children ) {\\74br /\\76    // do things with children\\74br /\\76  });\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76Promises are meant to be chainable and any promise returned in a `then` call will be automatically resolved and its result passed to the next `then`.'', ''timestamp'': ''1373481698684'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751373481698684#c9137058484922890611'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Josh David Miller'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-wQGrHgHMGow/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAKQ/gKGf1bmMhKE/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/10089217245214407451''}, ''displayTime'': ''July 10, 2013 at 11:41 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-2114264771''}, {''id'': ''279667887908738843'', ''parentId'': ''9137058484922890611'', ''body'': ''You\\46#39;re absolutely right. However, this has been gone over a few times in the comments, and I updated the article a (if you read the whole thing :P haha) while ago to reflect this. Perhaps I missed something?'', ''timestamp'': ''1373481994780'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751373481994780#c279667887908738843'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''July 10, 2013 at 11:46 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''2465943405730696840'', ''body'': ''Small correction:\\74br /\\76       return $http.get(\\46#39;foo.json\\46#39;).then(result) {\\74br /\\76           return result.data;\\74br /\\76       };\\74br /\\76should be:\\74br /\\76       return $http.get(\\46#39;foo.json\\46#39;).then(function(result) {\\74br /\\76           return result.data;\\74br /\\76       });\\74br /\\76in the \\46quot;Simplified Promise Pattern Example\\46quot; example. \\74br /\\76Thanks for the article!'', ''timestamp'': ''1374768891876'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751374768891876#c2465943405730696840'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Tanguy Le Barzic'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-8LZwqwfmGl0/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAgw/4fZUkKqahIE/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/01056438462514174043''}, ''displayTime'': ''July 25, 2013 at 9:14 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-916905565''}, {''id'': ''7486218675916966774'', ''parentId'': ''2465943405730696840'', ''body'': ''Heh.. yeah, silly typo on my part... good catch.'', ''timestamp'': ''1374786818900'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751374786818900#c7486218675916966774'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''July 25, 2013 at 2:13 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''3360701027765967250'', ''body'': ''Hey Benjamin,\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76Thanks for the tip! I\\46#39;m running into a little bit of a problem(I\\46#39;ve just started learning Angular, coming from Backbone).\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76I have your slick promise example working fine with a little Todo example I\\46#39;m making. However, when I implement a ng-click and try to access $scope.todos it looks like it is wrapped by a AngularJS object when it should just equal the Todo array returned by my Factory. See the deleteTodo function below:\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76var todoApp \\75 angular.module(\\46#39;todoApp\\46#39;, [])\\74br /\\76    .factory(\\46#39;todoFactory\\46#39;, function ($http) {\\74br /\\76      var factory \\75 {};\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76      // get from api example using promise pattern\\74br /\\76      factory.getTodos \\75 function () {\\74br /\\76        return $http.get(\\46#39;api/todo\\46#39;).then(function (result) {\\74br /\\76          return result.data;\\74br /\\76        }, function (reason) {\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76        });\\74br /\\76      };\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76      // delete from api example using promise pattern\\74br /\\76      factory.deleteTodo \\75 function (id) {\\74br /\\76        return $http({ method: \\46#39;DELETE\\46#39;, url: \\46#39;api/todo\\46#39;, data: { id: id } }).then(function (result) {\\74br /\\76          return true;\\74br /\\76        }, function (reason) {\\74br /\\76          return false;\\74br /\\76        });\\74br /\\76      };\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76      return factory;\\74br /\\76    }).controller(\\46#39;todoController\\46#39;, function ($scope, todoFactory) {\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76      init();\\74br /\\76      function init() {\\74br /\\76        $scope.todos \\75 todoFactory.getTodos();\\74br /\\76      }\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76      // ui event delete example\\74br /\\76      $scope.deleteTodo \\75 function ($index) {\\74br /\\76//////////////////////////\\74br /\\76///////// $scope.todos is wrapped by some AngularJS object(or the promise) instead of just /////////  being the todo array\\74br /\\76///////// $scope.todos \\75\\75 { $$v: [..the todo array..], then: function(){ ... }\\74br /\\76//////////////////////////\\74br /\\76        var todoToDelete \\75 $scope.todos[$index];\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76        todoFactory.deleteTodo(todoToDelete.id).then(function () {\\74br /\\76          $scope.todos.splice($index, 1);\\74br /\\76        }, function (reason) {\\74br /\\76          alert(\\46#39;there was an error\\46#39;);\\74br /\\76        });\\74br /\\76      };\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76    });\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76Thank you for the post!\\74br /\\76-alex\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\076'', ''timestamp'': ''1374934194253'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751374934194253#c3360701027765967250'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Alex Walchli'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh4.googleusercontent.com/-ORn8pdJgHqY/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAABU/FIQboz6FXXk/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/06853784213450783557''}, ''displayTime'': ''July 27, 2013 at 7:09 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-310837304''}, {''id'': ''7408246102750197222'', ''parentId'': ''3360701027765967250'', ''body'': ''Well, that\\46#39;s because technically it \\74i\\76is\\74/i\\76 wrapped by the angular promise. If you put a promise in a $scope.property in angular, when it binds the value in the view, it will get the value out of the promise. The scope.property itself is still a promise... if that makes sense.  If you need access to the data directly, it might be worth handling the promise\\46#39;s then and putting the value in a property or variable.\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76I hope that helps.'', ''timestamp'': ''1374976429470'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751374976429470#c7408246102750197222'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Benjamin Lesh'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh6.googleusercontent.com/-hdlSN8l__aI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAATg/mIiby_8gvQw/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/04866068949303979833''}, ''displayTime'': ''July 27, 2013 at 6:53 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-129846447''}, {''id'': ''2199455863115031307'', ''parentId'': ''3360701027765967250'', ''body'': ''Yep that makes sense.\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76I ended up changing my factory to just use the higher level $resource as opposed to $http.\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76.factory(\\46#39;todoFactory\\46#39;, function ($resource) {\\74br /\\76      return $resource(\\46#39;api/todos/:id\\46#39;);\\74br /\\76    });\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76No other changes were necessary in my controller. Thank you for your quick help!'', ''timestamp'': ''1375025529678'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751375025529678#c2199455863115031307'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Alex Walchli'', ''avatarUrl'': ''//lh4.googleusercontent.com/-ORn8pdJgHqY/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAABU/FIQboz6FXXk/s512-c/photo.jpg'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/06853784213450783557''}, ''displayTime'': ''July 28, 2013 at 8:32 AM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-310837304''}, {''id'': ''7198423965810543676'', ''body'': ''Thank you so much, just starting out with AngularJS and Javascript and while I had a high-level understanding of promises and how $http works, when it came to actually writing some code for the first time I was a little lost as to how it can be made to work together.  Your first examples were just what I was looking for!'', ''timestamp'': ''1381977446818'', ''permalink'': ''http://www.benlesh.com/2013/02/angularjs-creating-service-with-http.html?showComment\\0751381977446818#c7198423965810543676'', ''author'': {''name'': ''Aron'', ''avatarUrl'': ''http://img2.blogblog.com/img/b16-rounded.gif'', ''profileUrl'': ''http://www.blogger.com/profile/16473712911128102642''}, ''displayTime'': ''October 16, 2013 at 7:37 PM'', ''deleteclass'': ''item-control blog-admin pid-1222428576''}, {''id'': ''480463232652387920'', ''body'': ''Hey Benjamin, \\74br /\\76I am writing a directive to dump a list on a page based on html data I retrieve async from the database server.\\74br /\\76see below:\\74br /\\76I thought that \\46quot;MenuService.getMenuData().then\\46quot; would wait for the data but some how the directive ends before the data arrives.  I know I could put a timeout delay but that is not good.  Do you have a suggestion as to what could be the problem?\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76TBApp.directive(\\46#39;tbnavMenu\\46#39;, function ($compile, MenuService) {\\74br /\\76   var tbTemplate \\75 \\46#39;3empty\\46#39;;\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76    MenuService.getMenuData().then(function (val) {\\74br /\\76        tbTemplate  \\75 val;\\74br /\\76    });\\74br /\\76    \\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76    var getTemplate \\75 function () {\\74br /\\76        return tbTemplate;\\74br /\\76    }\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76    var linker \\75 function (scope, element, attrs) {\\74br /\\76  ...\\74br /\\76    }\\74br /\\76\\74br /\\76    return {\\74br /\\76        restrict: \\46quot;', '', '2014-02-24 09:42:48');
